    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the orb thing but it feels a bit too vague. can you explain the difference more clearly? like if i have two coins, what's the difference between them being \"classically correlated\" vs \"entangled\"?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! Imagine you have two coins. If the coins are classically correlated, it means they are connected by some hidden rule or mechanism. For example, if you flip one coin and it lands on heads, the other coin might also land on heads because they are linked by a secret agreement. You can't see this link, but it's there, like a hidden path between them.\n\nNow, if the coins are entangled, it's as if they are part of a magical, invisible string that connects them. When you flip one coin and it lands on heads, the other coin instantly flips to heads, no matter how far apart they are. This instant connection defies our usual understanding of space and time, like they're sharing a secret language that allows them to communicate instantly. It's like having two coins that are magically linked, and when one changes, the other changes at the same moment, even if they're on opposite sides of the world. That's the difference between classical correlation and quantum entanglement.",
      "source": "target",
