      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i think i get the gist but the \"magical\" part is still a bit confusing for an exam. physicists usually call this \"spooky action at a distance.\" why do they use a word like \"spooky\" to describe it? is there something actually weird or unsettling about how the particles interact?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, one of the greatest physicists of all time, to express his discomfort with the seemingly bizarre nature of quantum entanglement. He found it unsettling because it appeared to violate the fundamental principle of relativity, which states that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. In the world of quantum entanglement, the instant connection between entangled particles seemed to suggest that information could be transmitted faster than light, which was a mind-bending concept for Einstein.\n\nEinstein and his colleagues, including Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen, proposed a thought experiment called the EPR paradox to highlight this \"spooky\" aspect of quantum mechanics. They argued that if quantum mechanics were correct, it would imply that the universe was fundamentally incomplete, as it seemed to allow for instantaneous communication between distant particles.\n\nWhile the term \"spooky\" may seem odd, it was a way for Einstein to express his skepticism and discomfort with the strange and counterintuitive nature of quantum entanglement. Today, physicists have developed a deeper understanding of quantum mechanics, and while it still challenges our classical intuitions, it has been experimentally confirmed and is now a well-established aspect of the quantum",
      "source": "target",
